The main pharmacological purpose of hand washing is to remove pathogens (such as bacteria, viruses, or other microorganisms that can cause disease) and harmful or pathogenic chemicals from the hands.
It is an important practice for the general public, though it is especially important for those who handle food or work in the medical field.
Hand washing can lead to many health benefits, including reducing the transmission of influenza, coronavirus and other infectious diseases, preventing infections that cause diarrhoea, and reducing respiratory infections.
Then, there is a lower rate of infant mortality in home births.
